snippet.textDisplay: I would love to see you do a video on mental illness in a family member. My mom has bipolar disorder and chronic anxiety and growing up I never understood anything she did. She would go from barely speaking and sad about everything to being entirely volatile and OCD and manic. She would clean for hours even though nothing was dirty and if we got any toys out she would have a panic attack. I honestly hated her for a great portion of my life, especially in my teen years. It took me well into my adulthood to finally sit down and talk to her about how angry I was at the way i was treated. I never saw my mom cry so much, the guilt she felt was obvious and she admitted to me that she has suffered with the bipolar and anxiety her entire life and she just always tried to hide it or ignore it and she lived her life 40+ years trying to deal with the debilitating depression and mania. It put into perspective for me that she didn't do the things she did because she was cruel or selfish but she was suffering and the despair she felt caused her to never seek help, which she has just recently started after going through an eating disorder. She is actually laughing and happier now than I have ever seen her really and she loves to spend time with my son. I am just glad that I finally get to have a normal relationship with my mom, even though I am now 26 I feel like its never to late to try and move forward and respect the past for what it was (good or bad.)
